<span class=dateline>November  07, 2003</span> - It's Friday! That means we have a brand new "Ask SOE" for you today. This one features three new questions and answers with Steve "Moorgard" Danuser, the Community Manager for EverQuest II.<BR>
<BR></div></div><div id="intelliTxt"><div class="editorial">
As always, we encourage you to <A HREF="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?topic=59266722&replies=0">comment on this article</A> or just talk in general about EverQuest II on our <A HREF="http://vnboards.ign.com/board.asp?brd=22210">EQII General Board</A>.<BR>
<BR>
Please also send me questions for this, our EQ Q&A, our Lords of EverQuest Q&A or anything else at <A HREF="mailto:lepidus@vaultnetwork.com">lepidus@vaultnetwork.com</A>.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
<CENTER><B>Ask SOE - EQII Q&A #7</B><BR>
<I>With Steve "Moorgard" Danuser, Community Manager</I></CENTER><BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> One complaint against MMOs is the vast time commitments. What will EQII have that will draw in the more casual players? Not only in terms of less playing time, but short playing bursts.<BR>
 <BR>
<B>Steve "Moorgard" Danuser:</B> Our game is really designed around the idea of a group of friends being able to get together, group for a couple hours, and make meaningful progress in the game. We'll still have quests and other encounters that take significant time to complete, but they'll be broken up into shorter blocks of time rather than long camps that last six or eight hours.<BR>
<BR>
Through the careful use of instancing, we can make important quest mobs available to all players who have done the preliminary work necessary to reach that point in the quest. This way, we hope to avoid having multiple players waiting in line for their shot at a quest mob.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> Besides the obvious combat and crafting aspects, how much will there be for a player to do in the EQII world? What other types of things will be offered?<BR>
 <BR>
<B>Steve "Moorgard" Danuser:</B> The ever-popular pastime of fishing will be available to fill players' leisure hours, as will additional forms of gathering useful resources.<BR>
<BR>
Our intent is to add support for player-driven events such as combat tournaments, performances, and so on. One of our goals for EverQuest II is to have many ways to make our world compelling and rewarding beyond just having monsters to fight.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Lepidus:</B> Can you expand upon how your monster's AI will function? What different types of AI have you engineered to keep "player vs. environment" fresh and interesting?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Steve "Moorgard" Danuser:</B> Mobs now have an "area of interest" range in which they will react to you and give you visual feedback on how they feel about your presence. For example, you might stroll over a hill and find a group of Barbarians huddled around a campfire. Are these friendly ruffians or a bloodthirsty mob of brigands? When you enter their area of interest, the Barbarians will react to you. If they turn, draw their weapons, and enter a combat stance, you'll know they mean business. If you draw closer, they'll rush toward you and attack.<BR>
<BR>
The area of interest range is variable based on the particular mob you're facing. Wander into the lair of powerful dragon, for example, and she's not very likely to give you any warning before making you pay for your insolence.<BR>
<BR>
Of course, you'll also be able to click on mobs from a distance, which will give you an icon that tells you how they will react toward you. But area of interest allows us to give that extra bit of personality to NPCs and make our world feel that much more alive.<BR>
<BR>
Additionally, we can give mobs combat brains of varying complexity. More intelligent NPCs can use strategies and tactics against your party rather than simply attacking random targets. Players will have to be on their toes and adapt to these smarter opponents.<div class=byline>-- <a href="mailto:lepidus@vaultnetwork.com">Lepidus</A></div>
	</div>
</div>
